  <div class="small">
    <div class="column">
        <h4>Problem & Opportunity</h4>
      <div class="left-zeit">
        <p>Let’s imagine a young, driven milennial. They’ve just started their first job after college, and are passionate about making the most out of everyday. They love spending time with friends &amp; family, and want to make amazing memories with them. They’ve recently heard that after years of deliberation, officials have put in place standards to democratize the experience of time travel. They want to go on a trip, but don't know how to browse experiences, or buy tickets to travel back in time.</p>
        <div class="quote">
          <p>80% of people book travel online.</p>
        </div>
          <p>That shows people are comfortable with buying tickets online. I also looked at some of the reasons people hesitate booking travel online. <strong>One of the major contributors is an overly-complicated booking process.</strong></p>
          <p>This was a problem I felt passionate about – it is the perfect example of building an innovative product that helps people experience the world, while also positively affecting the business. I approached this iteratively, looking and learning at what truly gives people confidence to buy tickets online.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="small">
      <div class="column">
          <h4>User Research</h4>
        <div class="left-zeit">
          <p>My process began by collecting data from user interviews, competitive analysis, and secondary research.</p>
          <p>Our research goals were to identify our potential users, and empathize with problems they're currently facing in-regards to booking travel online.  Also, we wanted to gain a better understanding of their travel decision-making proces.  And, lastly, to gather more information about the travel tourism market.</p>
          <p>User research was followed by persona creation, building out an empathy map, and doing stroyboard exercises. What we learned right off the bat was that people want to be able to browse different catefories easily.</p>
          <p>Throughout the design process, I ran feedback sessions to collect user feedback and other stakeholders' insights into into an understandable view of Zeit's business goals, and if they were actually useful.</p>
              <img src="images/persona.png">
              <img src="images/empathy-map.png">
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="small">
      <div class="column">
        <div class="left-zeit">
          <h4>Interaction Design</h4>
          <p>Next, we focused on the organization of content. We started by making any sketches using pen &amp; paper, followed by sitemaps, task flows, and user flows.  All of this resulted in our first set of wireframes.</p>
          <p>Our V1 wireframes were good; a definite step in the right direction as it aligned with user needs and business goals, but there was still work left to do.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="small">
      <div class="column">
          <h4>UI Design</h4>
        <div class="left-zeit">
          <p>Our focus moved towards Visual Design, where we spent many hours designing a logo that was modern but still had a link to the past.  We followed that up putting together a brand style, and paid close attention to the mood of typography and the color palette.</p>
          <p>All of this work was truly gratifying, and spending time on making our designs pixel-perfect were worth it, since our next step was to collect more user feedback.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
